  $$RP-002$$,
  $$Hidden Debts & Philosophia: How Islam Rescued the Foundations of Western Thought. A ClownBinge Exclusive$$,
  $$european-renaissance-islamic-scholarship-primary-source-record$$,
  $$Between the 8th and 15th centuries, Muslim scholars preserved, translated, corrected, and extended the Greek and Roman scientific corpus that Europe had lost. The documents that launched the Scientific Revolution cite them by name.$$,
  $$<p>In 1543, <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Nicolaus Copernicus" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Nikolaus_Kopernikus_MOT.jpg/330px-Nikolaus_Kopernikus_MOT.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Nicolaus Copernicus was a Renaissance polymath who formulated a model of the universe that placed the Sun rather than Earth at its center. The publication of Copernicus&amp;amp;amp;#x27;s model in his book De revolutionibus orbium coelestium, just before his death in 1543, was a major event in the history of science, triggering the Copernican Revolution and making a pioneering contribution to the Scientific Revolution. Though a similar heliocentric model had been developed eighteen centuries earlier by Aristarchus of Samos, an ancient Greek astronomer, Copernicus likely arrived at his model independently." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-nicolaus-copernicus">Nicolaus Copernicus</span> published <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://www.loc.gov/item/46031925"><em>De Revolutionibus Orbium Coelestium</em></a>, the text that initiated the Copernican Revolution and reoriented Western astronomy away from the geocentric model inherited from <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Ptolemy" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Ptolemy_1476_with_armillary_sphere_model.jpg/330px-Ptolemy_1476_with_armillary_sphere_model.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Claudius Ptolemy, better known mononymously as Ptolemy, was a Greco-Roman mathematician, astronomer, astrologer, geographer, and music theorist who wrote about a dozen scientific treatises, three of which were important to later Byzantine, Islamic, and Western European science. The first was his astronomical treatise now known as the Almagest, originally entitled Mathēmatikḗ Syntaxis. The second is the Geography, which is a thorough discussion on maps and the geographic knowledge of the Greco-Roman world." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-ptolemy">Ptolemy</span>. The book cites one source by name 23 times. That source is not Greek. That source is not Roman. That source is a 9th-century Muslim astronomer named <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="al-Battani" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Al-Battani_-_Muḥammad_ibn_Jābir_al-Ḥarrānī_al-Battānī.jpg/440px-Al-Battani_-_Muḥammad_ibn_Jābir_al-Ḥarrānī_al-Battānī.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Al-Battani (c. 858–929 CE) was an Arab Muslim astronomer and mathematician who operated an observatory at Raqqa, Syria. His astronomical tables were cited 23 times by Copernicus in De Revolutionibus and used by Tycho Brahe, Kepler, Galileo, and Edmund Halley." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-al-battani">al-Battani</span>, who died in 929 CE, more than six centuries before the Renaissance began. The record says what it says. ClownBinge has reviewed it.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Battani"><span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Al-Battani" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/59/Latin_7266%3B_folio_78r_%28BnF%29.jpg/330px-Latin_7266%3B_folio_78r_%28BnF%29.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Al-Battani, archaically Latinized as Albategnius, was a Arab Muslim astronomer, astrologer, geographer and mathematician, who lived and worked for most of his life at Raqqa, now in Syria. He is considered to be one of the greatest and most famous of the astronomers of the medieval Islamic world." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-al-battani">Al-Battani</span>'s <em>Kitab az-Zij as-Sabi</em></a>, compiled around 900 CE at his private observatory in Raqqa, Syria, calculated the solar year at 365 days, 5 hours, 48 minutes, and 24 seconds (al-Battani, c. 900/1537). The modern accepted value differs from that figure by 2 minutes and 22 seconds, an error margin of approximately 0.00045 percent. His measurement of the Sun's eccentricity was more accurate than the values later obtained by both Copernicus and <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Tycho Brahe" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Portr%C3%A4tt_av_Tycho_Brahe_-_Skoklosters_slott_-_90153.tif/lossy-page1-330px-Portr%C3%A4tt_av_Tycho_Brahe_-_Skoklosters_slott_-_90153.tif.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Tycho Brahe, generally called Tycho for short, was a Danish astronomer known for his comprehensive and unprecedentedly accurate astronomical observations which helped to turn astronomy into the first modern science and launch the Scientific Revolution. He was known during his lifetime as an astronomer, astrologer, and alchemist. He was the last major astronomer before the invention of the telescope and has been described as the greatest pre-telescopic astronomer." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-tycho-brahe">Tycho Brahe</span> (Wikipedia contributors, 2025a). His tables were used by the German mathematician <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Christopher Clavius" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Portret_van_astronoom_Christoph_Clavius%2C_RP-P-OB-38.439_%28cropped%29.jpg/330px-Portret_van_astronoom_Christoph_Clavius%2C_RP-P-OB-38.439_%28cropped%29.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Christopher Clavius, was a Jesuit German mathematician and physicist, head of mathematicians at the Collegio Romano, and astronomer who was a member of the Vatican commission that accepted the proposed calendar invented by Aloysius Lilius, that is known as the Gregorian calendar. Clavius would later write defences and an explanation of the reformed calendar, including an emphatic acknowledgement of Lilius&amp;amp;amp;#x27; work. In his last years, he was probably the most respected astronomer in Europe and his textbooks were used for astronomical education for over fifty years in and even out of Europe." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-christopher-clavius">Christopher Clavius</span> to reform the Julian calendar, producing the Gregorian calendar adopted in 1582 and still in use today (Wikipedia contributors, 2025a). The calendar by which the Western world currently marks time was corrected using the work of a Muslim scholar from 9th-century Syria.</p><h2>The Bayt al-Hikma and the Arabic Translation Mandate</h2>
<p>The question of how Islamic scholarship reached Copernicus, Clavius, Kepler, and Galileo is not a matter of inference. It is a matter of documented translation history. In the 8th century CE, the <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Caliph Harun al-Rashid" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Harun_al-Rashid_and_the_Barber.jpg/440px-Harun_al-Rashid_and_the_Barber.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Harun al-Rashid (763–809 CE) was the fifth Abbasid caliph, ruling from 786 to 809 CE. He founded the library that would become the Bayt al-Hikma (House of Wisdom) in Baghdad and initiated the systematic collection of manuscripts from Greek, Persian, and Sanskrit sources." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-caliph-harun-al-rashid">Caliph </span><span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Harun al-Rashid" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2c/Gold_dinar_of_Harun_al-Rashid%2C_AH_170-193.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Abū Jaʿfar Hārūn ibn Muḥammad ar-Rashīd, or simply Hārūn ibn al-Mahdī, famously known as Hārūn al-Rashīd, was the fifth Abbasid caliph of the Abbasid Caliphate, reigning from September 786 until his death in March 809. His reign is traditionally regarded to be the beginning of the Islamic Golden Age. His epithet al-Rashid translates to &amp;amp;amp;quot;the Just&amp;amp;amp;quot;, &amp;amp;amp;quot;the Upright&amp;amp;amp;quot;, or &amp;amp;amp;quot;the Rightly-Guided&amp;amp;amp;quot;." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-harun-al-rashid">Harun al-Rashid</span> established in Baghdad a royal library and academic institution that his son <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Caliph al-Mamun" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7f/Al-Mamun.jpg/440px-Al-Mamun.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Al-Mamun (786–833 CE) was the seventh Abbasid caliph, ruling from 813 to 833 CE. He expanded the Bayt al-Hikma into a major intellectual center and dispatched diplomatic missions to the Byzantine Empire specifically to acquire Greek scientific manuscripts for translation into Arabic." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-caliph-al-mamun">Caliph al-Mamun</span> expanded into what is now documented as the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Bayt-al-Hikmah">Bayt al-Hikma</a>, or House of Wisdom, in Baghdad (Britannica, 2024). Al-Mamun dispatched diplomatic missions to the Byzantine Emperor specifically to acquire Greek manuscripts as a condition of peace treaties (Middle East Eye, 2024). More than 800 works of ancient Greek literature were procured under peace terms signed with the Byzantine Emperor <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Theophilus" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/93/Theophilus_Gould_Steward_1864.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Theophilus is a male given name with a range of alternative spellings. , it is a theophoric name, synonymous with the name Amadeus which originates from Latin, Gottlieb in German and Bogomil or Bogumił in Slavic." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikimedia Commons · Unknown authorUnknown author · Public domain" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-theophilus">Theophilus</span> (Middle East Eye, 2024). The Abbasid caliphs preferred manuscripts as war booty over gold. The documentary record confirms this preference in multiple contemporary Arabic sources.</p><h2>Al-Khwarizmi and the Algebra Naming Record</h2>
<p>Among the scholars working at the Bayt al-Hikma was <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="al-Khwarizmi" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Al-Khwarizmi_portrait.jpg/440px-Al-Khwarizmi_portrait.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Muhammad ibn Musa al-Khwarizmi (c. 780–850 CE) was a Persian polymath and mathematician who served as astronomer and head of the library at the Bayt al-Hikma in Baghdad. His treatise Al-Jabr, written around 820 CE, is the founding document of algebra as an independent discipline, and his name is the direct etymological origin of the word algorithm." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-al-khwarizmi">al-Khwarizmi</span>, appointed around 820 CE as astronomer and head of the library of the Bayt al-Hikma (Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). Between 813 and 833 CE, al-Khwarizmi compiled <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://archive.org/details/aljabar_alkhwarizmi"><em>Al-Kitab al-Mukhtasar fi Hisab al-Jabr wal-Muqabala</em></a>, translated into English as <em>The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion and Balancing</em> (Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). The word algebra is not a Latin word. It is not a Greek word. It is the Arabic word al-jabr, lifted directly from the title of al-Khwarizmi's manuscript, unchanged, into every European language that uses it (al-Battani, c. 900/1537; Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). The word algorithm derives from the Latinized form of al-Khwarizmi's own name, Algoritmi (Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). Every student who has ever taken an algebra class, written a line of code, or used a search engine is operating on infrastructure that carries a Muslim scholar's name in its etymology.</p><p>A unique Arabic manuscript of al-Khwarizmi's algebra treatise is held at the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://www.bodleian.ox.ac.uk">Bodleian Library at Oxford</a> (Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). A Latin translation is held at Cambridge. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Robert of Chester" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4a/StateLibQld_1_213292_Mrs_Robert_Chester_Master.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Robert of Chester was an English Arabist of the 12th century." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikimedia Commons · Item is held by John Oxley Library, State Library of Queensl · Public domain" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-robert-of-chester">Robert of Chester</span> translated al-Khwarizmi's text into Latin in 1145 CE at Segovia, under the title <em>Liber algebrae et almucabala</em> (Wikipedia contributors, 2025b). That Latin translation served as the principal mathematics textbook of European universities until the 16th century (Muslim Heritage, 2019). Not a supplementary text. Not a reference. The principal textbook. For four centuries of European mathematical education, the assigned reading was the translated work of a Muslim mathematician from 9th-century Baghdad.</p><h2>The Translation Pipeline into European Universities</h2>
<p>The mechanism by which Islamic scholarship entered European universities in organized, institutional volume is documented and named. It is called the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toledo_School_of_Translators">Toledo School of Translators</a>, operating under Archbishop Raymond of Toledo beginning in the 1120s CE (Wikipedia contributors, 2025c). Toledo had been a center of Islamic learning for centuries before its reconquest by Alfonso VI of Castile in 1085 CE. When Christian scholars arrived, they found libraries. They found libraries full of Arabic manuscripts containing the preserved and expanded works of Aristotle, Galen, Euclid, Ptolemy, and hundreds of Islamic scholars who had corrected, extended, and built upon those Greek foundations (Grokipedia, 2026). <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Gerard of Cremona" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Al-RaziInGerardusCremonensis1250.JPG/330px-Al-RaziInGerardusCremonensis1250.JPG" data-metricadiaid-desc="Gerard of Cremona was an Italian translator of scientific books from Arabic into Latin. He worked in Toledo, Kingdom of Castile, and obtained the Arabic books in the libraries at Toledo. Some of the books had been originally written in Greek and, although well known in Byzantine Constantinople and Greece at the time, were unavailable in Greek or Latin in Western Europe." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-gerard-of-cremona">Gerard of Cremona</span>, an Italian scholar who traveled to Toledo because he could not find Ptolemy's <em>Almagest</em> anywhere in Latin-speaking Europe, translated 87 books from Arabic into Latin before his death in 1187 CE (Wikipedia contributors, 2025c). Eighty-seven books. That single translator's output includes Ptolemy's <em>Almagest</em>, Aristotle's <em>Physics</em>, <em>On the Heavens</em>, <em>On Generation and Corruption</em>, and <em>Meteorology</em>, Euclid's <em>Elements of Geometry</em>, al-Khwarizmi's algebra treatise, and the foundational medical text of the entire European university system (Wikipedia contributors, 2025c).</p><p>That medical text is the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://www.loc.gov/item/2021667335/"><em>Al-Qanun fi al-Tibb</em></a>, or <em>Canon of Medicine</em>, completed in 1025 CE by the Persian physician and philosopher <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Ibn Sina" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/50/Ibn_Sina_-_2.jpg/440px-Ibn_Sina_-_2.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Ibn Sina (980–1037 CE), known in the Latin West as Avicenna, was a Persian polymath and physician who authored over 450 works across medicine, philosophy, mathematics, and astronomy. His Canon of Medicine remained the standard medical textbook at European universities for over six centuries, used at Montpellier as late as 1650 CE. Medieval Western scholars called him the Prince of Doctors." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-ibn-sina">Ibn Sina</span>, known in Latin Europe as Avicenna (Library of Congress, n.d.). Ibn Sina wrote the <em>Canon</em> in five books, systematically synthesizing Greek, Roman, Persian, Chinese, and Indian medical traditions while integrating his own documented clinical observations (Wikipedia contributors, 2025d). The <em>Canon</em> was translated from Arabic into Latin by Gerard of Cremona in the 12th century and became the standard medical textbook across European universities for more than six centuries (Library of Congress, n.d.). At the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Canon-of-Medicine">University of Montpellier</a>, one of Europe's oldest medical schools, it was still assigned reading in 1650 CE, more than six centuries after it was written (Britannica, 2024; PMC, 2013). Six centuries. That is longer than the United States has existed.</p><h2>The Structural Argument in the Primary Source Record</h2>
<p>The self-own here is structural. The contemporary political argument that Islamic civilization is incompatible with Western intellectual values requires, as a foundational premise, that Islamic civilization made no foundational contribution to Western intellectual values. The primary source record does not support that premise. It contradicts it on every axis simultaneously. The word the West uses for its foundational mathematical discipline is Arabic. The astronomer Copernicus cited 23 times in the book that launched modern astronomy is Muslim. The medical textbook that trained European physicians for six centuries was written by a Muslim scholar in Bukhara. The translation pipeline that delivered Aristotle, Euclid, and Ptolemy back to Europe ran through Islamic Spain. These are not contextual footnotes to Western intellectual history. They are load-bearing structural facts. ClownBinge makes no judgment about the political arguments currently being made. The documents make the argument on their own.</p><p>The translation pipeline itself requires documentation beyond a single institution, because its scale is often underestimated. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Hunayn ibn Ishaq" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Hunain_ibn_Ishaq_al-Ibadi.jpg/440px-Hunain_ibn_Ishaq_al-Ibadi.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Hunayn ibn Ishaq (808–873 CE) was a Nestorian Christian Arab physician and scholar who served as chief translator under Caliph al-Mamun at the Bayt al-Hikma in Baghdad. He translated more than 100 Greek medical texts into Arabic and Syriac, including works by Galen, Hippocrates, and Dioscorides, and documented his translation methodology in a systematic bibliography." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-hunayn-ibn-ishaq">Hunayn ibn Ishaq</span>, the chief translator under Caliph al-Mamun, translated more than 100 Greek medical texts into Arabic and Syriac, including the majority of Galen's surviving corpus (Gutas, 1998). He documented his own translation methodology in a systematic bibliography, one of the earliest examples of translation theory as a formal discipline. The translation movement he led was not incidental to Islamic civilization. It was state-sponsored, institutionally organized, and conducted at a scale that had no parallel in the contemporary Latin West (Gutas, 1998). While the Latin West was restricted to the fragments of Aristotle's logical writings, Islamic scholars were working with Aristotle's complete corpus, correcting it, commenting on it, and extending it into new domains of inquiry.</p><p>The commentaries produced by Islamic scholars on Aristotle were not marginal annotations. They became required reading at European universities. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Ibn Rushd" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Averroes_Cordova.jpg/440px-Averroes_Cordova.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Ibn Rushd (1126–1198 CE), known in the Latin West as Averroes, was an Andalusian Muslim philosopher and physician who produced extensive commentaries on Aristotle&amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;#x27;s complete works. His commentaries became mandatory texts at the University of Paris and other European universities, earning him the title The Commentator in Western scholastic tradition." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-ibn-rushd">Ibn Rushd</span>, known in Latin Europe as Averroes, produced commentaries on Aristotle's complete works from his base in Cordoba, al-Andalus (Wikipedia contributors, 2025e). European scholastics called him simply <em>The Commentator</em>, a title reserved for one scholar across the entire Latin tradition. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Thomas Aquinas" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Saint_Thomas_Aquinas.jpg/440px-Saint_Thomas_Aquinas.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Thomas Aquinas (1225–1274 CE) was an Italian Dominican friar and Catholic theologian whose systematic theology, the Summa Theologica, is considered the foundational text of Catholic intellectual tradition. Aquinas built his theological framework directly on Aristotelian philosophy as transmitted through Averroes&amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;#x27;s Arabic commentaries and the Toledo translation movement." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-thomas-aquinas">Thomas Aquinas</span>, the foundational theologian of Catholic intellectual tradition, built the Aristotelian framework of the <em>Summa Theologica</em> directly on Averroes's commentaries as transmitted through Toledo (SIL in Eurasia, n.d.). The philosophical architecture of Catholic doctrine as it exists today was constructed, in documented part, on the work of a 12th-century Muslim philosopher from Islamic Spain.</p><h2>The Astronomical Record Beyond al-Battani</h2>
<p>The astronomical record extends beyond al-Battani. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="Nasir al-Din al-Tusi" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Nasir_al-Din_Tusi.jpg/440px-Nasir_al-Din_Tusi.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Nasir al-Din al-Tusi (1201–1274 CE) was a Persian polymath and astronomer who founded the Maragheh Observatory in northwestern Iran in 1259 CE. He saved thousands of manuscripts from the Mongol destruction of Baghdad by relocating them to Maragheh, and his Tusi couple mathematical device was later used without attribution in Copernicus&amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;#x27;s De Revolutionibus." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-nasir-al-din-al-tusi">Nasir al-Din al-Tusi</span>, anticipating the Mongol destruction of Baghdad, moved thousands of manuscripts to the <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="cb-factoid" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maragheh_observatory">Maragheh Observatory</a> in northwestern Iran in 1259 CE (Middle East Eye, 2024). A geometric device al-Tusi developed at Maragheh, now documented in the scholarly literature as the Tusi couple, appears in Copernicus's <em>De Revolutionibus</em> (Wikipedia contributors, 2025f). Copernicus did not cite al-Tusi for this device. Al-Battani he cited 23 times. Al-Tusi's geometric contribution he used without attribution. The De Revolutionibus Wikipedia contributors entry for the heliocentric model documents that it made use of the Urdi Lemma developed by the 13th-century Arab astronomer Mu'ayyad al-Din al-Urdi (Wikipedia contributors, 2025f). The Copernican Revolution, the foundational event of Western scientific modernity, was built on a documented stack of Islamic astronomical work.</p><h2>The Medical Record: Ibn Sina and the Canon</h2>
<p>The medical record is equally precise. By 1025 CE, when Ibn Sina completed the <em>Canon of Medicine</em>, the Islamic world had already produced a documented tradition of clinical medicine that European institutions would not independently replicate for centuries. <span class="metricadiaid-marker" data-metricadiaid-name="al-Razi" data-metricadiaid-image="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Rhazes_%28al-Razi%29_-_MS_P_284.2_-_Wellcome_Images.jpg/440px-Rhazes_%28al-Razi%29_-_MS_P_284_2_-_Wellcome_Images.jpg" data-metricadiaid-desc="Muhammad ibn Zakariyya al-Razi (854–925 CE), known in Latin as Rhazes, was a Persian physician who served as chief physician at the Baghdad hospital and the Ray hospital. He wrote the first documented clinical distinction between smallpox and measles, and his encyclopedic medical work Kitab al-Hawi was translated into Latin and used in European university curricula." data-metricadiaid-attribution="Wikipedia / Wikimedia Commons" role="button" tabindex="0" data-testid="metricadiaid-al-razi">Al-Razi</span>, known in Latin Europe as Rhazes, produced the first documented clinical distinction between smallpox and measles in the 9th century CE, a differential diagnosis European medicine would not systematically apply for centuries after his death (PMC, 2009). His encyclopedic work <em>Kitab al-Hawi</em> was translated into Latin and incorporated into European university medical curricula alongside Ibn Sina's <em>Canon</em> (PMC, 2009). The two primary textbooks of European medical education for the medieval and early modern periods were both written by Muslim physicians from Persia. This is not a marginal data point. It is the documented institutional record of European medical education.</p><p>ClownBinge has reviewed the full primary source stack. The Arabic unique manuscript of al-Khwarizmi's algebra treatise sits in Oxford. The Latin translation sits in Cambridge. The <em>Canon of Medicine</em> sits in the Library of Congress. <em>De Revolutionibus</em>, with its 23 citations of al-Battani, sits in the Library of Congress. The Toledo translation records, the Gerard of Cremona <em>Vita</em> and <em>Commemoratio librorum</em> compiled by his students after his death, document 87 specific titles transmitted from Arabic into Latin. The Gregorian calendar, the algebra curriculum, the astronomical tables, the medical textbooks, the Aristotelian philosophy underlying Catholic doctrine. The record is not a footnote to Western civilization. The record is a foundational layer of it.</p><p>The manuscripts do not make a political argument. They have call numbers.</p>$$,
  'reasons_pen',
  $$De Revolutionibus Orbium Coelestium (1543) — Library of Congress::Copernicus, N. (1543). De revolutionibus orbium coelestium. Petreius. https://www.loc.gov/item/46031925; Canon of Medicine Manuscript (c. 1025) — Library of Congress::Ibn Sina. Al-Qanun fi al-Tibb [Manuscript]. Library of Congress. https://www.loc.gov/item/2021667335/; Al-Jabr Manuscript (c. 820) — Bodleian Library, Oxford::Al-Khwarizmi. Al-Kitab al-Mukhtasar fi Hisab al-Jabr wal-Muqabala [Arabic manuscript, trans. F. Rosen]. Bodleian Library, University of Oxford.; Kitab az-Zij as-Sabi [De motu stellarum] (c. 900/1537) — Printed Latin Edition::Al-Battani. (Plato of Tivoli, Trans.). Petreius. Original work composed c. 900 CE.; Bayt al-Hikmah — Encyclopaedia Britannica (2024)::Britannica. Bayt al-Hikmah. https://www.britannica.com/place/Bayt-al-Hikmah; The Canon of Medicine — Encyclopaedia Britannica (2024)::Britannica. The Canon of Medicine. https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Canon-of-Medicine; Greek Thought, Arabic Culture — Gutas (1998)::Gutas, D. (1998). Greek thought, Arabic culture: The Graeco-Arabic translation movement in Baghdad and early Abbasid society. Routledge.; Al-Battani — Wikipedia::Wikipedia contributors. (2025). Al-Battani. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Battani; Al-Khwarizmi — Wikipedia::Wikipedia contributors. (2025). Al-Khwarizmi. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi; Toledo School of Translators — Wikipedia::Wikipedia contributors. (2025). Toledo School of Translators. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toledo_School_of_Translators; Ibn Sina (Avicenna) — Wikipedia::Wikipedia contributors. (2025). Avicenna. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avicenna; De Revolutionibus — Wikipedia::Wikipedia contributors. (2025). De revolutionibus orbium coelestium. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_revolutionibus_orbium_coelestium; Ibn Sina's Canon — PubMed Central (2013)::Masic, I., et al. Thousand-year anniversary of the Canon of Medicine written by Ibn Sina. PubMed Central. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3702097/; House of Wisdom — Middle East Eye (2024)::Middle East Eye. Baghdad: The House of Wisdom — Uniting East and West to pursue knowledge. https://www.middleeasteye.net/discover/iraq-baghdad-house-wisdom-uniting-east-west$$,
  '{"islam","philosophy","western_thought","intellectual_history","medieval","reasons_pen","erased_history"}',
  'published',
  '2026-04-07T03:38:25Z',
